02F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_240,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 240w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_320,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 320w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_640,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 640w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_960,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 960w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_1280,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 1280w","height":853},"xxl":{"width":1600,"url":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_1600,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png","srcset":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_120,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 120w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_240,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 240w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_320,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 320w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_640,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 640w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_960,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 960w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_1280,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 1280w, https:\u002F\u002Fassets.vogue.com\u002Fphotos\u002F686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a\u002Fmaster\u002Fw_1600,c_limit\u002F0EWoS-richemont-group-growth-by-nationality.png 1600w","height":1067}}}},"level":"block","ref":"686e6a89d263477a717f8d3a","type":"image"}],["p","If the rapid rise of India’s middle class and billionaires (the number of which jumped from 70 to 284 in the past decade, according to ",["em","India Today"],") once gave luxury brands hope of becoming the next China, the reality — centuries-old, highly skilled Indian jewellers, combined with cultural norms where the Western concept of an engagement ring feels alien — has forced a reassessment."],["ad",{"position":"mid-content"}],["p","“The reason Western jewellers struggle in India was plain to see at the ",["a",{"href":"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.voguebusiness.com\u002Fstory\u002Fconsumers\u002Fhow-the-ambani-wedding-could-redefine-indias-massive-industry","class":"text link","isExternal":false},"Ambani wedding"],",” quips Bvlgari CEO Jean-Christophe Babin (the wedding showcased styles that are popular in India, such as nose rings, anklets and head ornaments, which Western jewellers typically do not include in their core ranges). Bvlgari was among the first to acknowledge both the challenges and the opportunities, enlisting ",["a",{"href":"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.voguebusiness.com\u002Fstory\u002Ffashion\u002Fbeyond-bollywood-the-new-playbook-for-indian-brand-ambassadors","class":"text link","isExternal":false},"Priyanka Chopra"]," as ambassador and launching a ",["a",{"href":"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.voguebusiness.com\u002Fstory\u002Fconsumers\u002F3-opportunities-for-brands-eyeing-indias-luxury-market","class":"text link","isExternal":false},"Bvlgari version of the mangalsutra"],", a necklace traditionally worn by married women in India."],["p","But the issue with Indian jewellers is not simply — unlike in China — their strength in the local market. The real threat is their global expansion, offering jewellery that matches Western maisons in quality and seduces with innovative design beyond the obvious customer base made by the Indian diaspora."],["p","Leading the charge is Sabyasachi Mukherjee, founder of the eponymous brand Sabyasachi, which is now stocked at Bergdorf Goodman in New York and partnered with King Charles and Queen Camilla on the Elephant Family charity event last year. More recently, Viren Bhagat — whose pieces were worn by members of the Ambani family — opened a showroom in London’s Mayfair. Santi Jewels, founded by a 10th-generation member of the Choudhary family of gemstone collectors, has exhibited at the Tefaf Maastricht art centre and held trunk shows across the US."],["p","Yet the rise of Chinese and Indian brands may also present opportunities for Western luxury groups, following Kering’s lead as the first to dip its toes into the market with an investment in Qeelin. After all, jewellery’s resilience hasn’t been accidental: it has been strategically built by remaining laser-focused on clients’ evolving needs and meeting them across every price point and aesthetic desire, even those they didn’t know they had."],["p",["strong","Key takeaway:"]," Thanks to a rational approach to pricing, investment appeal, cultural relevance and ability to meet customers at every price point, jewellery brands have defied the luxury downturn. Growth has been driven by signature, repeatable designs known as icons; however, a strategic effort to elevate existing icons and create new ones is needed to avoid the threat of ubiquity and counterfeits. When it comes to global markets, the rise of Chinese and Indian jewellers challenges European dominance, but also presents opportunities."]],"pageStructure":[["p",54],["p",86],["inline-embed",200,"image"],["native-ad",0],["p",84],["inline-embed",-100,"cneinterlude"],["p",52],["cm-unit",0],["p",61],["native-ad",0],["p",19],["h2",9],["p",108],["ad",0],["p",91],["p",12],["p",64],["p",101],["i